answers.body_markdown:
[`java.util.Currency`][1] provides the necessary information. A reasonable approach to print currency values without the currency sign in pure Java code is to get a general-purpose [`NumberFormat`][2] instance and configure it to use the number of digits defined by the appropriate `Currency` object:

    NumberFormat numberFormat = NumberFormat.getInstance(myLocale);
    Currency currency = Currency.getInstance(myLocale);
    numberFormat.setMinimumFractionDigits(currency.getDefaultFractionDigits());

If you need a specific currency as opposed to the default currency of the locale you use, use [the `String` override of `Currency.getInstance()`][3] instead and provide the appropriate currency code.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/util/Currency.html
