# Details

Let&#39;s make your example code more concrete. Instead of `MyEnum`, we call that `CodeLetter`. Instead of `MyClass`, we use `java.time.DayOfWeek`. 

Firstly, it seems the `key` field is just a distraction, unrelated to your Question. So we reduce that to a simple enum declaration. 

```java
public enum CodeLetter { A, B, C; }
```

We provide an implementation for the `helper` class you mention. Pass one of the `CodeLetter` enum objects, get back a `DayOfWeek` object.

```java
DayOfWeek helper ( final CodeLetter codeLetter ) {
    DayOfWeek dow =
            switch ( codeLetter ) {
                case A -&gt; DayOfWeek.SATURDAY;
                case B -&gt; DayOfWeek.SUNDAY;
                case C -&gt; null;
            };
    return dow;
}
```

Now implement fully your example method that builds a map. 

 - We rename that method from `myMethod` to `buildMap`. 
 - We rename `result` to `map` for clarity.
 - We eliminate the argument to that method, as it seems irrelevant. 
 - There is no such class nor method `Maps.newHashMap`, so we replace that with a specific class that implements `Map`. When you have an enum as your map key, use the highly optimized [`EnumMap`][1] class.
 - `Optional&lt;MyClass&gt;`, would be `Optional&lt;CodeLetter&gt;` with our new naming. But `Optional` is generally best used only as a return type. In our case here, `EnumMap` allows for map values to be null. So we forgo the `Optional` to use simple null instead. 

```java
private Map &lt; CodeLetter, DayOfWeek &gt; buildMap ( ) {
    Map &lt; CodeLetter, DayOfWeek &gt; map = new EnumMap &lt;&gt; ( CodeLetter.class );
    for ( CodeLetter codeLetter : CodeLetter.values ( ) ) {
        DayOfWeek dow = this.helper ( codeLetter );
        map.put ( codeLetter , dow );
    }
    return map;
}
```

Exercise this code.

```java
EnumMapExample app = new EnumMapExample ( );
Map &lt; CodeLetter, DayOfWeek &gt; map = app.buildMap ( );
System.out.println ( &quot;map = &quot; + map );
```

When run:

